image shows \u003Cstrong\u003Enormal oesophageal mucosa\u003C/strong\u003E with its characteristic salmon-pink colour. The photograph has been taken several centimetres proximal to the squamo-columnar junction. The rugal folds of the cardia are visible just distal to the junction. There is no evidence of \u003Cstrong\u003EBarrett\u0027s oesophagus\u003C/strong\u003E, which would appear as red, velvet-like columnar epithelium extending above the gastro-oesophageal junction (Image 1). \u003Cstrong\u003EOesophageal candidiasis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents as white plaques adherent to the mucosa (Image 2). \u003Cstrong\u003EReflux oesophagitis\u003C/strong\u003E would show erythema, erosions or ulceration (Image 3). \u003Cstrong\u003ESquamous cell carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E would appear as an irregular, ulcerated mass lesion (Image 4).\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ol\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Normal oesophageal mucosa appears salmon-pink with visible vasculature on endoscopy","The gastro-oesophageal junction is marked by a clear squamocolumnar junction (Z-line)","Endoscopic assessment requires systematic evaluation of mucosal colour, texture, and anatomical landmarks"],"references":["Lu J, Wang Q, Zhang H, Liu J, Ren J, Fan J, Gong J, Sui Y, Chen X. Analysis of endoscopic and pathological features of 6961 cases of gastric cancer. Sci Rep. 2024 Mar 26;14(1):7159. doi: 10.1038/s41598-024-58018-6. PMID: 38532198; PMCID: PMC10965891.","Ahlawat R, Hoilat GJ, Ross AB. Esophagogastroduodenoscopy. [Updated 2023 Aug 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK532268/","\u0022Stomach endoscopy\u0022 by Ignis is licensed under Creative Commons Attribution-Share Alike 3.0 Unported license. https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Stomach_endoscopy_1.jpg","Zhang L, Gerson L, Maluf-Filho F. Systematic review and meta-analysis in GI end